03596nam a22005055i 9780520384712DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203847127 a10.1525/97805203847122doi  a(DE-B1597)627305  a(OCoLC)1320821012  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHV6250.4.H66bM495 2022 7aSOC0010002bisacsh04a362.88392086/64223/eng/202205251 aMeyer, Doug, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aViolent Differences :bThe Importance of Race in Sexual Assault against Queer Men /cDoug Meyer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Understanding Sexual Assault against Queer Men through the Lens of Intersectionality -- t1. “Why Didn’t You Fight Back?”: Black Queer Male Survivors and Discourses of Blame -- t2. Queer Male Survivors and Police Interactions -- t3. Survivors’ Self-Blame and Differences within the Queer Umbrella -- t4. Racial Differences Regarding Emasculation -- t5. Constructing Hierarchies of Victimhood -- t6. Outing, Disclosing Marginalized Identities, and Navigating Multiple Stigmas -- tConclusion: Future Challenges and Possibilities -- tAppendix: Methods -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite rising attention to sexual assault and sexual violence, queer men have been largely excluded from the discussion. Violent Differences is the first book of its kind to focus specifically on queer male survivors and to devote particular attention to Black queer men. Whereas previous scholarship on male survivors has emphasized the role of masculinity, Doug Meyer shows that race and sexuality should be regarded as equally foundational as gender. Instead of analyzing sexual assault against queer men in the abstract, this book draws attention to survivors’ lived experiences. Meyer examines interview data from sixty queer men who have suffered sexual assault, highlighting their interactions with the police and their encounters with victim blaming. Violent Differences expands approaches to studying sexual assault by considering a new group of survivors and by revealing that race, gender, and sexuality all remain essential for understanding how this violence is experienced.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGaysxViolence against. 0aMale rape victimszUnited Statesy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520384712?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520384712423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520384712/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY